	<div id="welcome">
		<h2 class="title"><a href="#">Welcome!</a></h2>
		<div class="entry">
			<p>I am statistician whose interests and motivations revolve around ecology and epidemiology (or perhaps, an ecologist with a formal background in statistical modeling).  Currently, I am working toward a PhD in Peter Hudson's lab at Penn State's <a href="http://www.cidd.psu.edu">Center for Infectious Disease Dynamics</a>. My research interests broadly include application of spatial and temporal modeling techniques as they relate to understanding disease transmission processes. </p>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div id="page">
		<div id="page-bgtop">
			<div id="page-bgbtm">
				<div id="content">
					<div class="post">
						<h2 class="title"> Research Interests and Philosophy</h2>
						<div class="entry">
							<p>I am interested in modeling processes that operate over space and time. Some cases I find particularly exciting are spatiotemporal patterns in disease transmission, natural selection along environmental gradients, and shifting patterns in habitat use. These processes have several common components.  Ecologically, all three are mechanistically driven by species' behavioral patterns, which likely emerged in response to evolutionary pressures.  Statistically, each can be framed in models that link predictors (including the status of spatially and temporally proximal classes) to categorical (and often multivariate) responses. Physically, they all reflect a process responding to the local matrix resistance. From a modeling perspective, these processes are engaging because they are both mathematically and statistically tractable (and challenging). I'm particularly interested in developing methodologies that explicitly link between mechanistic predictions provided through mathematical models and statistical signals recovered from empirical data.  </p>
						</div>
					</div>
				</div>
